				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cybersqyd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5336470); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=5336470&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610177564" alt="cybersqyd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=5336470)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cybersqyd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5336470); return false;" >cybersqyd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1609416841 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">31 Dec 2020 12:14</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4858301">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Open&nbsp;for&nbsp;crit</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I'm not really a fan of the central narrative section; it feels&#8230;too expected and too focussed on the backstory of this. My general advice when writing a SCP is to forget about why it exists (and how the Foundation found it, a little). In general, backstory is not the most interesting angle because it happens a) before the foundation get involved (and so, before any of the PoV characters can be there) and b) it's just, not very interesting; and this suffers from this a lot since there's not really any way for the Foundation to know about the mans' gradual discovery of his powers, not a lot happens while he discovers them, and it's very temporally removed from the here and now and the people involved in the story.</p>
<p>Like, at the end of the day, you're trying to write an interesting short story about a weird thing, not an actual technical report on it; and so you really have to figure out why the weird thing existing is interesting and how it's existence affects the Foundation: like, do they use this man as like, a living transcriber? Do they run experiments on him? Does his ability pose difficulties because of some unforeseen aspect of them?</p>
<p>Part of my concern here is that the effects of the man are very&#8230;straightforward? One of the really hard parts of writing a scp is balancing the anomalous properties so that they're complex enough that you can do something interesting to explore what they mean whilst also not creating a big, overcomplex mess of properties that's hard for a reader to understand whilst also not being interesting. <a href="/yourjouney-part-1">The Journey of Your First SCP: Part I</a> talks about this a lot when it discusses 'depth vs complexity': at the moment, your anomaly is neither complex nor deep, and so there's not a lot of interesting things that it like&#8230;leads to a person being able to do; and I think this is why you're struggling a little to find the interesting thing here.</p>
<p>My suggestion would be to consider the emotions here: like, maybe there's an interesting angle where you can explore the effect that being in containment has on the man, and how it makes 'em feel; or perhaps you can figure out a reason for him to be in some like, really severe containment and so in turn, make a reader feel empathically sad at the Foundations treatment of him, or something.</p>
<p>It might be worth having a read of e.g. <a href="/an-exercise-in-narrative-based-scps">An exercise in narrative based SCPs</a> and <a href="/how-not-to-walk-your-dog-pacing-essay">How Not to Walk Your Dog: An Essay on Pacing</a> to really get a feel for like, how to do something interesting with the SCP idea.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

